text: Part 2: The Show  Manitoba is often called the epicentre of the MMIWG2S+ crisis—but it is also the root of our resurgence. I was honoured to be invited by Manitoba designer @lindsayking.co to be part of her groundbreaking merging of advocacy and fashion. A social worker with more than 20 years of working with Indigenous children and families, The Red Collection is Lindsay’s response to recommendation #4 of the Final Report of the National Inquiry into Missing and Murdered Indigenous Women and Girls. There are many ways to keep the conversation about MMIWG2S+ going: through work in the Legislature, through advocacy on the frontlines, through action and through art. The Red Collection is one way to show Indigenous women are still here, sharing our skills and strengths and gifts for our collective healing and the resurgence of future generations. Miigwech to advocates like Lindsay who continue to centre Indigenous women in powerful ways, in Manitoba and beyond.

text: Four new agreement types have been added to the Child and Family Services Act, which came into effect on October 1 2024. These agreements provide CFS agencies with more options to keep parents actively involved in planning for their children while they retain guardianship and access additional support.   Agreements:   Kinship Care: This is an agreement between the parent, the caregiver, and an agency, where children live with a kinship who provides care within the child’s community with the participation of the family. A kinship caregiver has a family connection or a significant relationship with the child or the parent. Customary Care: This is an agreement between the parent, the caregiver, and an agency, where children live with a customary caregiver in a way that reflects the unique customs of the child’s Nation. Customary care is led by individual Nations. Family Support: This is an agreement to provide supports that meet the needs of a child and their family so children can stay at home or return home. Voluntary Care: This is an agreement between the parent and an agency, where children live in a foster or group home and care is provided to a child on a voluntary basis outside of the child’s home.

text: On Thursday Bill 38 — AN ACT RESPECTING CHILD AND FAMILY SERVICES (INDIGENOUS JURISDICTION AND OTHER AMENDMENTS) — received Royal Assent , becoming Law in Manitoba.  Bill 38 ensures no legislative obstacles or impairments to Indigenous jurisdiction of child welfare.  Bill 38 is history in the making laying the legislative foundation of bringing our children home.  Child welfare in Manitoba will look very different in the next many years as more and more First Nations and Metis take over the care of their children, youth and families.  I dedicate Bill 38 to our beautiful children, now and in the future.🪶❤️

text: Introducing Manitoba’s tallest mural, a new landmark gracing the heart of Treaty 1. Titled Giizaagiigo — “You Are Loved”— this mural honours Indigenous women, girls and 2Spirit, celebrating our strength, resilience and beauty. Murals are profound symbols in our communities. Winnipeg is home to over 600 murals, each a unique story. Yet Giizaagiigo stands apart — not just as a stunning artistic piece, but as a tribute to the enduring strength of our women.  Cora and I knew from the beginning this project we wanted to commission Jeanie Whitebird — a gifted artist known for her vibrant community murals across Treaty 1 — to bring our vision to life. Together with her mural partner, Charlie Johnston, Jeanie captured the essence of our vision. Cora guided the design process, refining the final imagery embodying the spirit of our intention. They were phenomenal to work with.   Giizaagiigo is a testament to the pride, empowerment and safety our Indigenous women, girls, and 2Spirit deserve. It stands on the land of our ancestors, who withstood generations of trauma and oppression, as a beacon of love and resilience. Miigwech to my sister and colleague, Minister Bernadette Smith, and her team for partnering with us to place this mural on the Manitoba Housing building at 444 Kennedy. When Cora identified this building as the perfect canvas, I reached out to Minister Smith, who graciously and wholeheartedly approved.  A heartfelt Miigwech to our community partner, Sandra Delaronde of Giganawenimaanaaig, for her unwavering commitment to our women, girls, and 2Spirit relatives. Miigwech to Cora Morgan for your vision. Miigwech to Kevin Settee for capturing this beautiful work of art.  A profound Miigwech to Jeanie Whitebird and Charlie Johnston, whose artistry has brought Giizaagiigo to life. To all Indigenous women, girls, and 2Spirit people … YOU. ARE. LOVED.

text: Yesterday’s announcement on decolonizing child welfare in Manitoba marks a significant step forward in empowering our communities and supporting our children. As of October 1st, child welfare agencies in Manitoba now have four legislative tools to keep children out of court, bring them home, and keep families together.  These agreements allow children to remain with their parents, in kinship care, or under customary care, with parents maintaining guardianship and playing an active role in planning for their children. * Family Care: Children stay in their home with supports. * Kinship Care: Children live with a kinship caregiver (Kokum, auntie, cousin, etc.) with supports. * Customary Care: Children live with a customary caregiver (community) with supports. * Voluntary Care: Children live in foster or group homes through an agreement between the parent and the agency. Miigwech to Southeast CFS for hosting the announcement.  Miigwech to Chief Young and Chief Bluesky for your presence and support.  Miigwech to Cynthia Broadfoot for bravely sharing your CFS experience.  Miigwech to the Kinship and Foster Family Network of Manitoba for attending and supporting this important work. Together, we are decolonizing child welfare in Manitoba and building a future rooted in culture, community, and reconciliation.

text: One of our first announcements last year was should we form government we would institute free birth control.  This October 1st that becomes a reality in Manitoba.  Free birth control reduces unintended pregnancies, lowering health risks associated with pregnancy and childbirth. Free birth control helps in managing and treating reproductive health conditions.  Free birth control supports Manitoban’s participation in the workforce by planning pregnancies around their schooling, training and careers — which ultimately contributes to Manitoba’s economic growth. Free birth control reduces healthcare costs associated with unintended pregnancies, including prenatal care, delivery and abortion services. Free birth control fundamentally contributes to gender equality by ensuring women, girls and gender diverse folks have the same opportunities as men in education, employment and personal development. Free birth control helps in breaking the cycle of poverty. Free birth control allows women to choose if or when or whom they choose to marry or have relationship with based on their own personal and career considerations. Free birth control is a powerful tool in dismantling patriarchal systemic inequities.  A special Miigwech to Minister Asagwara and their team for working so hard to get this done on behalf of our government and to the benefit of all Manitobans! Yesterday’s announcement was a great day!

text: First, I’m fine. I remain unfazed and unapologetic.  I’ve been contemplating whether or not to share this. Last week, two incidents finally made up my mind for me. These, just the latest in years of similar experiences. First, a man (in a subordinate position) attributed what I’ve been saying, recommending and directing for months to another man.  How often have women been in meetings or conversations, voicing their ideas, only to have a man credit those ideas to another man?  No matter what space women occupy, we’ve all experienced this scenario. A few days later, at a pow wow in the Grand Entry, standing in line with all the other dignitaries, Elders, dancers, etc., another public servant intentionally did not shake my hand. On reserve land, during an Indigenous ceremony, a non-Indigenous man chose not to shake the hand of an Indigenous woman and Minister of the Crown.  He didn’t apologize. In the last months, my house has been egged, the front glass door of my constituency office smashed and several weeks after that, a knife thrown at my office windows.  So why am I sharing all this? The DMs, comments, actions, misogynistic rumours and disrespect I experience, even as an elected official and Minister of the Crown, reflects the same disrespect and risk many of us face in our various spaces/positions. No space is immune from men’s disregard or contempt. But there’s a particular vitriol reserved for Indigenous, Black, POC women, and gender-diverse folks. It’s this vitriol that pushes BIPOC women and gender-diverse folks out of these respective spheres. And what’s the typical response to this? “Don’t say anything.” “It will only make it worse or become a bigger story.”  So men’s behaviours go unchecked and the patriarchy remains unbothered. I prefer to post empowering, uplifting, encouraging stories, particularly in honour of women, on my IG account.  But - I’ve never been silent on anything. Ever. It goes against my very nature.  It shouldn’t be this hard to be respected.  To all the women and gender diverse folks experiencing similar disrespect, erasure and violence, know I see you.  Reel inspired by @jackiecamardo  #smashthepatriarchy

Miigwech to Chief Cindy Daniels for welcoming our Manitoba Team onto Cowichan Territory to discuss your Indigenous Law over child welfare.  Miigwech to Victoria Native Friendship Centre‘s Executive Director Ron Rice for the visit and sharing the impressive work you folks are doing in community.  Chief Daniels: “we are a matrilineal People and look who’s sitting around the table.”  Indeed. We understand and live this sacredness.

text: This morning, in front of the first trans man ever elected to the Manitoba Legislature, four Members of the PC Caucus got up on the House floor and voted against our NDP colleague Logan Oxenham’s Bill 208 — The Two-Spirit and Transgender Day of Visibility Act. Four PCs voted against this bill and AGAINST trans and two-spirited Manitobans, and even more abstained from the vote entirely; including some who aspire to be the leader of their party.  This is more than a vote against a bill.  It’s a vote against Manitobans’ humanity.  It’s a vote against every person trying to live as their authentic self.  It’s a vote against protecting trans kids and letting them grow into the adults they deserve to be.  It’s a vote against real people in the very families, neighbours, and communities they’ve been elected to represent.  It’s disgusting. And yes, that’s me saying such in the video.  When someone shows you who they are, believe them.  This PC Party shows us who they are again and again and again and again. #transrightsarehumanrights #transrights #twospirittiktok #twospirit #pride

text: Reading headlines from the past or a dystopian future?  Nope. It’s right now.  Politicians, predominantly men, both in the U.S. and Canada, are seeking to, or have already outright banned access to abortion and other reproductive health services.  Now US Politicians are seeking to restrict access to birth control.  Specifically, we learned today that one state is passing legislation to categorize the abortion pill as an illicit controlled substance. You know - like heroin or LSD.   What they’re imposing amounts to draconian abortion bans - and they’re also coming after IVF procedures as well as threatening Physicians with jail time and fines.  And we know that what happens in the US often flows up to Canada. We’ve already seen attempts at legislation like the “Unborn Victims of Crime Act”, polling on limiting abortion access, and petitions for the unborn being tabled.  The importance of fighting against trying to control women - because that is the core issue - and the rollback of reproductive rights cannot be overstated.  Abortion is healthcare. This procedure is required for a myriad of health concerns. Sometimes it’s the only procedure that will keep a woman from dying.  We all know that restricting access to abortion does not eliminate the demand for it; it often forces individuals to seek unsafe and clandestine procedures, again putting their lives at risk. Complacency in the face of these challenges is  dangerous.  Keep your foot off my uterus and stop trying to control us!

text: Yesterday, Premier @Wab Kinew and I took concrete and ceremonial steps to decolonize the child welfare system and restore the inherent rights of Indigenous children, families, communities and Nations.  Our Peoples have always centred our children — they are the fire and motivation of our culture and traditions.  We signed a Declaration with First Nation Rights Holders affirming the right of First National to have the care and control of their children and their welfare.  First Nations have a full partner in our Government in transferring jurisdiction of child welfare.  Yesterday, and the days, months and years ahead, are exciting times and I look forward as Minister moving us on the path of reconciliation and jurisdiction.🩷

authorMeta.name: nahannifontaine
authorMeta.signature: Mom. Matriarch. Feminist. Minister of Families.

text: Today was a historic day in Manitoba.  Premier Wab Kinew, and myself, as Minister of Families, signed a Relationship Declaration for First Nations Child Welfare Jurisdiction with First Nation Rights Holders.  The Declaration is our Government’s commitment to transferring jurisdiction of child welfare back to Nations, communities and families — where it should have has always rested. It affirms First Nation children have inherent rights, including being cared for by their Nation, community and families.  Our Government will work with First Nations in their pursuit of jurisdiction as a committed and respectful partner.  We are decolonizing child welfare once and for all.

text: Yesterday, on Red Dress Day 2024, I was so happy to realize a dream I’ve had for the last 10 to 15 years as we gathered at the Canadian Museum for Human Rights, surrounded by the National Inquiry’s sacred bundle.  I was honoured to announce the establishment of the MMIWG2S Healing and Empowerment Endowment Fund.  Our government’s investment of $15 million dollars will generate grants for years to come. Managed by the Winnipeg Foundation, our initial investment is expected to generate up to $750,000 a year. These grants will be used to support MMIWG2S families and Indigenous-led organizations working directly to prioritize the protections of Indigenous women, girls and two-spirited.  For years, Manitobans have asked me “what can I do to support MMIWG2S?”  The MMIWG2S Healing and Empowerment Endowment Fund will be accepting donations from citizens, from corporate entities and the like.  Yesterday’s announcement is in honour of MMIWG2S families whose resiliency, courage and love paved the way for us as government to do this good work. #mmiwg2s #mmiwgawareness #reddress

text: On this National Ribbon Skirt Day, I’m reflecting on the growth of our ribbon skirts over these last fifteen years and what they mean and feel to us as Indigenous women.  We bond over our ribbon skirts.  We represent our style, our Peoples, our territories, our culture in our ribbon skirts.  We’re empowered in our ribbon skirts.  We take up and reclaim space in our ribbon skirts.  We artisan ribbon skirts.  We protect in our ribbon skirts.  We ceremony in our ribbon skirts.  We laugh in the way only Indigenous women laugh in our ribbon skirts.  We survive in our ribbon skirts.  We thrive in our ribbon skirts. We love in our ribbon skirts.  *my ribbon skirt by @brandi_meeches_ribbon_skirts  The beautiful, talented and so very intelligent Marcy Large bonding over our skirts.  #ribbonskirts
